fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.71) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.11. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 14.99 (S.E. = 2.39, p < .001, 95% CI [10.30, 19.69]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.06, S.E. = 0.04, p = 0.137, 95% CI [-0.02, 0.14]; Std. beta = 0.22, 95% CI [-0.07, 0.52])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -1.46, S.E. = 1.16, p = 0.206, 95% CI [-3.72, 0.80]; Std. beta = -0.37, 95% CI [-0.94, 0.20])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.71, S.E. = 0.80, p = 0.371, 95% CI [-2.28, 0.85]; Std. beta = -0.18, 95% CI [-0.58, 0.22])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.80, S.E. = 1.20, p = 0.001, 95% CI [1.46, 6.15]; Std. beta = 0.96, 95% CI [0.37, 1.56])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
